        {
            "id": "12.5",
            "type": "lesson",
            "title": "Natal di Indonesia Timur",
            "titleEn": "Christmas in eastern Indonesia",
            "content": {
                "intro": "Eastern Indonesia has unique Christmas traditions, including barapen (hot stone cooking) in Papua and bamboo cannons in Flores.",
                "sentences": [
                    {
                        "id": "Yosef terima kartu Natal dari Danny.",
                        "en": "Yosef receives a Christmas card from Danny."
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "Pesta Barapen adalah tradisi bakar batu untuk memasak daging babi.",
                        "en": "Barapen is a tradition of using hot stones to cook pork."
                    },
                    {
                        "id": "Sambil mendengarkan lagu Natal, Yosef berkumpul dengan keluarga.",
                        "en": "While listening to carols, Yosef gathers with his family."
                    }
                ],
                "grammar": {
                    "title": "'Kan — Confirmation Tag",
                    "explanation": "**'Kan** comes from bukan. Used as a tag to confirm shared knowledge: *Sudah ada isinya, 'kan?* (It has content, hasn't it?). Colloquial — spoken only.",
                    "examples": [
                        {
                            "id": "'Kan sudah ada isinya.",
                            "en": "Well, it already has content, hasn't it?"
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "Besok libur, 'kan?",
                            "en": "Tomorrow is a holiday, isn't it?"
                        }
                    ]
                },
                "culturalNote": "In Papua, traditional barapen parties use hot stones to cook pork as a sign of Christmas joy. In Flores, bamboo cannons explode on Christmas Eve."
            },
